} const Experience = () => {

public Experience job(Time time){

Intro to programming - teacher assistant

Under the supervision of titular professor Marc Feeley and lecturer Olivier Melançon I worked alongside 7 other students to teach and grade a class of almost 300 on the basics of programming - through python.

Discrete structures for computer science - teacher assistant

Under the supervision of titular professor Miklós Csűrös I worked with a Masters student to teach and grade a class of 100 on the discrete structures from mathematics that we most commonly use as computer scientists.

}

} const Projects = () => {

Projects:

Gesture recognition web application (Flask and tensorflow)

Developed during a 2 month period with a team of 3. You can check it out here
My teammates trained the model while I learned Flask and made a web application, front to back
It remains unfinished, some animations are missing and files can't yet be uploaded, but I'll come back to it with more experience.

Vaccination management system

A functioning app developped with Java that includes a graphical interface and a data management system.
I had a hand in the planning and design of the project, and wrote around 95% of the 2000 lines of code in it, plus documentation.
As requested by the teaching staff of that class, the code is private.
Currently on its last stage of development.

Counters

School project for object oriented programming with java; its a small window:

Using JavaFX, we (2 people) made a fancy window with 2 counters: you can add and substract, divide and
multiply, undo and redo, and export a .txt file with all registered operations
You can download the .zip of the project or you can see it on Github
Warning: it is in french

Pseudo-Lisp interpreter made with Haskell

Built the interpretation and evaluation section of a Haskell program that could read and execute files from a Lisp inspired language. Dealt with functions, closure, environments, variables, etc... the whole enchilada.

Pseudo-Haskell interpreter made with Prolog

Same thing, but this time it was a Haskell-inspired language and using Prolog for reading and executing.
Out of respect of the professor's code that compiled before our interpreter played any role, the code is private.
Currently on its last stage of development.

OOP Environment simulation made with Java

DISCLAIMER: The image presented is not from the project (the project only prints to the terminal).
It is merely illustrative and from a game called "Wild Lion Simulator 3D".

Using objected oriented programming we made an environmental simulation program.
It read XML files describing animals or plants and simulated them for a certain amount of epochs: the way they interacted,
what they ate, their energy consumption, whether they died or reproduced, and so on.

This website!

Made from scratch with html , css , javascript , jquery as well as the Animate on Scroll library. And a sprinkle of love!

} const Interests = () => {

let interests =

Web development

I'm particularily interested in all the ways computers communicate with each other, and how to make that experience as people-friendly as possible.

Computer Graphics

There's just something so fascinating about all the little math and psychology tricks behind making a 2D screen and a fancy calculator fool a person into thinking they're looking at a 3D object. I also like being fooled with pretty, non existant, 3D objects myself.

On top of that GPUs are by far the fastest developping computer component nowadays. I'd really like to better understand how they work, to exploit their full potential.

Game development

A natural progression from my interest in graphics, as well as my long-lived love for games - video or otherwise.

I feel like game development would let me be my most creative self, and that's someone I'd like to meet.

Immunity

I'm mostly interested in how immune cells communicate and navigate. I have a very strong feeling that there is space for a lot more computer science in this field, but I have yet to figure out how.

Robotics

Ok honestly if you don't think robots are at least a little cool we can't be friends.

On a more serious note, robotics seems like the future of physical processes and manipulations, everywhere from medicine to manufacturing and transport.
That sounds pretty cool.

Compilation and Operating Systems

Specially how to deal with very limited physical space and adverse physical conditions for the hardware.

I'm interested in knowing how we could program computers that don't get the same luxuries in stability and space as our normal computers.
How could we ensure good and reliable code in these environments?

} const Accolades = () => {

Pretty medals!

December 2021: DIRO's excellence scholarship

An excellence scholarship awarded to a few bachelor students by my department

August 2020: Exemption Scholarship for international students

Biggest merit-based scholarship for international students at the Université de Montréal

2019: French regional math olympiads | Best team, Top 3 individual

My region spanned from Mexico to Panama, and included all french teaching institutions there.
